27    /**
28    * A DataModel manages a set of data and (optionally) a corresponding
29    * set of meta-data. While DataNodes can be used stand-alone, and
30    * also combined with MetaNodes without a DataModel, this is the class
31    * which ties it together and integrates it with other mechanisms.
32    * Most importantly it adds a transaction and subscription system for
33    * data value changes, to keep track of changes and notify subscribers,
34    * implementing these aspects of the DataHandle interface. Most data
35    * access is handled through the DataModelHandle implementation of
36    * DataHandle, so client code will usually not have direct access to
37    * the DataModel.
38    * <p>
39    * The model keeps one or several data node trees. The first one is
40    * the main and default one, and is unnamed. One data structure is
41    * sufficient for most uses, but the model supports having additional
42    * data instances, useful for cases where we need to process data from
43    * multiple sources/documents together while keeping them distinct for
44    * reading/writing from/to files etc. A colon is used to specify a
45    * named instance. <code>:x/y/z</code> refers to a node z in a node y
46    * under the root of an instance named x. Meta data can be defined for
47    * any instance. Meta data is optional, and we can have data without
48    * meta data, but if we want meta data for a node then any parent node
49    * also must have meta data (/a/b can't have meta data if /a doesn't
50    * have meta data).
51    * <p>
52    * The DataModel interface is mainly for initialization and management
53    * of the model, with the DataHandle interface handling data access.
54    * DataModel supports parsing/serialization, such as reading/writing
55    * XML or JSON, through DataSerializer objects. It provides the
56    * framework for reading/writing from streams, especially files, to
57    * be configured or extended in sub-classes. It can for instance be
58    * connected to a file, reading initial content from a file and
59    * persisting changes to the file every time a transaction completes
60    * with changes.
61    * <p>
62    * Once the model has been initialized, any operation which may change
63    * data values must run as a transaction. The DataHandle has the
64    * transaction interface for data updates. Some DataModel operations,
65    * such as adding meta data or resetting all values to their meta
66    * defaults, are complete transactions in themselves. The model has
67    * a mechanism for client code to subscribe to changes in data, with
68    * DataUpdateSubscribers registered through the DataHandles. A related
69    * mechanism is that of DataProvider, which is an object which
70    * provides values for some data in the model.
71    * <p>
72    * Another key concept is DataProcessor. This is an object which
73    * updates the value(s) of nodes based on changes in other nodes,
74    * typically representing a relationship between data, such as a
75    * mathematical function. The DataModel can create DataProcessors by
76    * parsing expressions with data paths and operators, so that it can
77    * implement numerical and boolean expressions from strings. With
78    * this expression parsing, DataModel also support defining conditions
79    * for rules. Adding Trigger and Action objects, DataModel can be
80    * used as a basic rule engine for Trigger-Condition-Action rules.
81    * <p>
82    * A typical way to use DataModel is to first add MetaData to define
83    * the model schema, along with any DataProcessors and DataProviders
84    * needed. Then we can initialize the model with either the contents
85    * of a file or with the default values specified by the meta. Then
86    * we get a DataHandle to read, write and subscribe to data.
87    *
88    * @author Lars Thomas Boye, Tellu AS
89    */

560    /**
561    * Add meta-data to the model. The MetaNode added can be a group
562    * with a tree of child nodes. The path may be null or an empty
563    * String to add the meta below the root of the main instance,
564    * otherwise it can specify the path of any MetaNode previously
565    * added.
566    * <p>
567    * Meta-data should mainly be added before the model is
568    * initialized, setting up the initial structure. At this stage
569    * no transaction is needed, and any meta can be added, replacing
570    * any existing meta with the same name under the same path.
571    * It is also possible to add additional meta or replace meta
